{"type_article": "Article", "title": "Rethinking how built environments influence subjective well-being: a new conceptual framework", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/17549175.2017.1310749", "author_list": ["Kostas Mouratidis"], "journal_name": "Journal of Urbanism: International Research on Placemaking and Urban Sustainability Volume 11, 2018 - Issue 1", "date": " 04 Apr 2017", "abstract": "This paper aims to contribute to understanding the role of the built environment in subjective well-being (SWB\n. The paper presents a new conceptual framework that integrates and links together: (a) different sets of objective and perceived neighborhood characteristics, (b) different perspectives on SWB \u2013 hedonic, life satisfaction, and eudaimonic, and (c) mediating factors that explain how neighborhood characteristics influence SWB. These mediating factors are personal relationships, leisure activities, health, and neighborhood impact on emotions and mood. SWB can be a new powerful tool for planning and designing livable built environments and for evaluating the social sustainability of planning policies.", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.1080/17549175.2017.1310749", "keyword_list": ["Keywords:", "Urban planning", "sustainability", "happiness", "livable", "city", "quality of life"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["Alexander, C., S. Ishikawa, and M. Silverstein. 1977. A Pattern Language: Towns, Buildings, Construction. Vol. 2. New York: Oxford University Press.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "American Planning Association. n.d. \u201cWhat is Planning?\u201d https://www.planning.org/aboutplanning/.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Ballas, D. 2013. \u201cWhat Makes a \u2018Happy City\u2019?\u201d Cities 32: S39\u2013S50.10.1016/j.cities.2013.04.009[Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Barton, H. 2009. \u201cLand Use Planning and Health and Well-being.\u201d Land Use Policy 26: S115\u2013S123.10.1016/j.landusepol.2009.09.008[Crossref], [Web of