{"type_article": "Article", "title": "Effect of mine tailings on the  in situ  survival of walleye ( Stizostedion vitreum ) eggs in a northern Ontario river", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/11956860.1994.11682245", "author_list": ["Amy L. Leis", "Michael G. Fox"], "journal_name": "\u00c9coscience Volume 1, 1994 - Issue 3", "date": " 24 Mar 2016", "abstract": "We investigated the effects of a gold mine tailings spill on the survival of walleye (\n) eggs in a northern Ontario river. The spill, which occurred in the fall of 1990, dumped 300 000 tonnes of fine tailings with high concentrations of heavy metals that were dispersed along a 5-km stretch of the Montreal River. Eggs were collected from resident walleye, artificially fertilized and reared in small plexiglass incubators that held 50 eggs each. Incubators were placed on the substrate and in the water column in control and tailings sites in May 1992 and 1993. Mortality in the substrate incubators averaged 64% at control sites and 81% at tailings sites, and was significantly higher in the latter in both years. Temperature, pH, dissolved oxygen, water velocity, conductivity and alkalinity were monitored at each site during the incubation experiments. No significant correlations were detected between egg mortality and any of these factors. In 1993, suspended sediment was collected at incubation sites. Significantly higher concentrations of lead, copper, and nickel were found in tailings sites, whereas there was no significant difference between control and tailings sites in suspended sediment quantity. Egg mortality was significantly correlated with the concentration of lead (r\n = 0.50) and copper (r\n = 0.57). Our results suggest that the higher mortality of walleye eggs in the tailings sites was due to metal toxicity and/or hypoxia from the resuspension and settling of mine tailings.", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.1080/11956860.1994.11682245", "keyword_list": ["Key Words:", "early life-history", "metal toxicity", "mortality", "walleye", "sediment toxicity", "water quality", "Mots-cl\u00e9s::", "histoire naturelle", "toxicit\u00e9 m\u00e9tallique", "mortalit\u00e9", "dor\u00e9 jaune", "toxicit\u00e9 des s\u00e9diments", "qualit\u00e9 de l\u2019eau"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["Auer, M. T. & N. A. Auer, 1990. Chemical suitability of substrates for walleye egg development in the Lower Fox River, Wisconsin. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 119: 871\u2013876.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Auer, N. A. & M. T. Auer, 1987. Field evaluation of barriers to walleye egg and larva survival in the Lower Fox River, Wisconsin. American Fisheries Society Symposium, 2: 93\u2013101.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Beattie, J. H. & D. Pascoe, 1978. Cadmium uptake by rainbow trout, Salmo gardneri eggs and alevins. Journal of Fish Biology, 13: 631\u2013637.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bedard, D. & S. Petro, 1991. Montreal River study laboratory sediment bioassay report. Water Resources Branch, Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Rexdale, Ontario.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Campbell, D. & I. Marshall, 1991. Mining. Pages 11.1\u201311.25 in The State of Canada\u2019s Environment. Government of Canada, Ottawa.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Colby, P. J., R. E. McNichol & R. A. Ryder, 1979. Synopsis of Biological Data on the Walleye Stizostedion v. vitreum (Mitchell 1818). F.A.O. Fisheries Synopsis no. 119. Food and Agricultural Organization of the United Nations, Rome, Italy.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Corbett, B. W. & P. M. Powles, 1986. Spawning and larva drift of sympatric walleyes and white suckers in an Ontario stream. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 115: 41\u201346.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "de Souza, H. A. F., 1991. Mineralogy and Chemistry of the Matachewan Tailings. Miscellaneous Paper 157, Geoscience Laboratories, Ontario Geological Survey, Ontario Ministry of Northern Development and Mines.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "F\u00f6rstner, U., 1987. Sediment-associated contaminants. An overview of scientific bases for developing remedial options. Hydrobiologia, 149: 221\u2013246.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Fox, M. G., 1993. A Comparison of zygote survival of native and non-native walleye stocks in two Georgian Bay rivers. Environmental Biology of Fishes, 38: 379\u2013383.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Hulsman, P. F., P. M. Powles & J. M. Gunn, 1983. Mortality of walleye eggs and rainbow trout yolk-sac larvae in low-pH waters of the Lacloche Mountain Area, Ontario. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 112: 680\u2013688.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Johnson, F. H., 1961. Walleye egg survival during incubation on several bottom types in Lake Winnibigoshish, Minnesota, and connecting waters. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 90: 312\u2013322.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Luoma, S. N., 1983. Bioavailability of trace metals to aquatic organisms. A review. The Science of the Total Environment, 28: 1\u201322.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "McKim, J. M. & D. A. Benoit, 1971. Effects of long-term exposures to copper on survival, growth, and reproduction of brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis). Journal of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada, 28: 655\u2013662.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Moore, J. W. & S. Ramamoorthy, 1983. Heavy Metals in Natural Waters. Springer-Verlag, New York.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Mudroch, A., 1991. Preliminary Study of the Mine Tailings Spill at Matachewan, Ontario. Lake Research Branch, National Water Research Institute.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Ontario Geological Survey, 1990. Analysis of Geological Samples volume 2, Manual of Methods. Miscellanous Paper 149, Geoscience Laboratories, Ontario Geological survey, Ontario Ministry of Northern Development and Mines.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Ontario Ministry of the Environment, 1983. Handbook of Analytical Methods for Environmental Samples. Volume 2.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Ozoh, P. T. E., 1979. Malformations and inhibitory tendencies induced to Brachydanio rerio (Hamilton-Buchanan) eggs and larvae due to exposures to low concentrations of lead and copper ions. Bulletin of Environmental Contamination and Toxicology, 21: 668\u2013675.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Ozoh, P. T. E., 1980. Effects of reversible incubations of zebrafish eggs in copper and lead ions with or without shell membranes. Bulletin of Environmental Contamination and Toxicology, 21: 668\u2013675.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Persuad, D., R. Jaagumagi & A. Hayton, 1991. Provincial Sediment Quality Guidelines. Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Toronto, Ontario.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Pitlo, J. J., 1992. Walleye and Sauger (Stizostedion spp.) in the Upper Mississippi River: Early Life History. Fish Technical Section Upper Mississippi River Conservation Committee, Rock Island, Illinois.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Reynoldson, T. B., 1987. Interactions between sediment contamination and benthic organisms. Hydrobiologia, 149: 53\u201366.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Richard, P. D. & J. Hynes, 1986. Walleye Culture Manual. Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Siefert, R. E. & W. A. Spoor, 1974. Effects of reduced oxygen on embryos and larvae of the white sucker, coho salmon, brook trout, and walleye. Pages 487\u2013495 in J. H. S. Blaxter (ed.). The Early Life History of Fish. Springer-Verlag, New York.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Sly, P. G., 1988. Interstitial water quality of lake trout spawning habitat. Journal of Great Lakes Research, 14: 301\u2013315.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Smith, L. L. & R. H. Kramer, 1963. Survival of walleye eggs in relation to wood fibers and Sphaerotilus natans in Rainy River, Minnesota. Transactions of the American Fisheries Society, 92: 220\u2013261.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Sokal, R. R. & F. J. Rohlf, 1981. Biometry, 2nd edition. W. H. Freeman and Company, New York.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Tessier, A. & P. G. C. Campbell, 1987. Partitioning of trace metals in sediments: Relationships with bioavailability. Hyd