{"type_article": "Article", "title": "Risks associated with the use of new materials in construction", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/135993799349126", "author_list": ["John   Manning"], "journal_name": "Technology, Law and Insurance Volume 4, 1999 - Issue 1-2", "date": " 05 Nov 2010", "abstract": "The process of construction traditionally has involved the reworking of naturally occurring materials to form a new topography or to build structures. The one-off nature of construction renders prototype testing impractical, and hence specifications have been built up on a recipe basis justified by previous satisfactory performance. More innovative designs, whole life costing, design/build/operate procurement and the influence of European integration requires that materials control assumes an even more important role in construction. The relationship between material properties ascertained from one-dimensional testing and assumptions made in threedimensional computer simulation requires particular care with massive structures and geotechnical modelling, as does the change in properties with time. Product testing and European legislation are emerging as important commercial considerations for components, but care is needed on how these are integrated into construction projects. Consideration of timescale and conclusive testing often is restrictive when evaluating new materials or products, as are open ended objectives in performance. Finally, the emerging importance of risk assessment specifically related to materials selection and component performance is seen as a more rigorous way of influencing decision making.", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.1080/135993799349126", "keyword_list": ["Keywords:", "Recipe Specifications", "Product Testing", "Quality Assurance", "Materials Control", "Whole Life", "Costing", "Materials Properties", "Computer Modelling", "Influence Of Design", "Ec Products", "Directive"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["CIRIA. 1993. The Impact of European Communities' Policy on Quality Management in Construction, Special Publication 89 London: Construction Industry Research and Information Association. \u00a0[Google Scholar]", "EN1. 1992. EN1 - Euro Code 1: Basis of Design and Actions on Structures, CEN/TL250. \u00a0[Google Scholar]", "MacLeod, I.A., Kumar, B. and McCullough, J. 1998. Innovative design in the construction industry. Civil Engineering Proceedings, 126: 31\u201338. \u00a0[Google Scholar]", "H & S. 1994. The Construction (Design and Management) Regulations 1994, Statutory Instrument No. 3140 London: Health and Safety, HMSO. \u00a0[Google Scholar]", "ICE. 1991. The ICE Conditions of Contract , 6th Edn, London: The Institution of Civil Engineers. \u00a0[Google Scholar]"]}
{"type_article": "Article", "title": "Late effects on the health-related quality of life in a cohort population decades after environmental radiation exposure", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.3109/09553002.2013.784423", "author_list": ["Pimei Nancy Yen", "Chen-Chang Yang", "Wushou Peter Chang", "Jung-Der Wang", "Jing-Shiang Hwang", "Tien-Chun Chang", "Kuan-Liang Kuo", "I-Feng Lin"], "journal_name": "International Journal of Radiation Biology Volume 89, 2013 - Issue 8", "date": " 22 May 2013", "abstract": ": To evaluate the late effects on the quality of life (QOL) of individual years after protracting low-dose radiation exposure.\n: We assessed 1,818 subjects using the World Health Organization Questionnaire on Quality of Life \u2013 Brief Version (WHOQOL-BREF) in several Health-Related Quality of Life (HRQoL) domains. After adjusting for demographic characteristics and comorbidities, we examined the HRQoL differences at various levels of exposure and ages at disclosure. We also evaluated the potential effect modification by gender.\n: After adjusting for potential confounders, girls aged 12 years or younger at the disclosure of exposure had lower HRQoL scores in physical, psychological, and environmental domains compared to those with later age at disclosure. The differences in the HRQoL scores between different exposure subgroups were not significant in physical, psychological, and social relationship domains, and only appeared in the environmental domain.\n: Being female and less than 12 years of age at disclosure were more significant predictors of HRQoL scores than the levels of radiation exposure among people exposed to protracted low-dose radiation. Further studies are needed to determine the psychological distresses, such as depression and anxiety, and their relationships in this case, especially for the most vulnerable young females.", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.3109/09553002.2013.784423", "keyword_list": ["Keywords::", "Health-related quality of life", "late effect", "perception risk", "prolonged low-dose-rate radiation exposure", "Taiwan", "WHOQOL-BREF"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["Beehler GP, Baker JA, Falkner K, Chegerova T, Pryshchepava A, Chegerov V, Zevon M, Bromet EJ, Havenaar J, Valdismarsdottir H, et al. 2008. A multilevel analysis of long-term psychological distress among Belarusians affected by the Chernobyl disaster. Public Health 122:1239\u20131249.[Crossref], [PubMed], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bender R, Lange S. 2001. Adjusting for multiple testing \u2013 when and how?. Journal of Clinical Epidemiology 54:343\u2013349.[Crossref], [PubMed], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bromet EJ. 2012. Mental health consequences of the Chernobyl disaster. Journal of Radiological Protection 32:N71\u201375.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bromet EJ, Havenaar JM, Guey LT. 2011. A 25 year retrospective review of the psychological consequences of the Chernobyl accident. Clinical Oncology 23:297\u2013305.[Crossref]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bromet EJ, Gluzman S, Schwartz JE, Goldgaber D. 2002. Somatic symptoms in women 11 years after the Chornobyl accident: prevalence and risk factors. Environmental Health Perspectives 110:625\u2013629.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Cardarelli Jn, Elliott L, Hornung R, Chang WP. 1997. Proposed model for estimating dose to inhabitants of 60Co contaminated buildings. Health Physics 72:351\u2013360.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Chang TC, Chen WL, Chang WP, Chen CJ. 2001. Effect of prolonged radiation exposure on the thyroid gland of residents living in 60Co-contaminated rebar buildings. International Journal of Radiation Biology 77:1117\u20131122.[Taylor & Francis Online]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Chang WP. 1993a. Taiwan: Exposure to high doses of radiation. The Lancet 341:750.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Chang WP. 1993b. Spread of Taiwan's radiation panic. The Lancet 342:1544.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Chang WP, Chan CC, Wang JD. 1997a. 60Co 