{"type_article": "Article", "title": "The Relationship Between State Government Performance and State Quality of Life", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1081/PAD-120024400", "author_list": ["Jerrell   D.   Coggburn", "Saundra   K.   Schneider"], "journal_name": "International Journal of Public Administration Volume 26, 2003 - Issue 12", "date": " 07 Feb 2007", "abstract": "This article examines the relationship between government performance and quality of life in the American states. We contend that the management capacity of state governments should have direct, tangible impacts on the \n social and economic well\u2010being of state citizenry. In order to test this idea, we examine the influence of state management capacity (using the 1999 Government Performance Project grades), alongside other economic and political variables, on two prominent measures of state quality of life\u2014The Morgan Quitno \u201cMost Livable State\u201d Index and \n (SPP) \u201cCamelot Index.\u201d We find that both state economic conditions and governmental policy priorities have significant impacts on state performance levels. But, our results clearly indicate that the management capacity of state governments also contributes directly to improving the overall quality of life for state citizens. ", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.1081/PAD-120024400", "keyword_list": ["Keywords:", "Public management", "State quality of life", "Government performance", "Management capacity", "State policy priorities", "State government"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["Poister, T. H. and Streib, G. 1999. Performance measurement in municipal government: assessing the state of practice. Public Admin. Rev., 59(4): 325\u2013335. [Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Mihm, C.  Beyond plans, promises and good intentions: instilling results\u2010oriented management in federal agencies. Meeting the Challenges of Performance\u2010Oriented Government. Edited by: Newcomer