{"type_article": "Article", "title": "Business retention and expansion and business clusters \u2013 A comprehensive approach to community development", "link": "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/15575330.2017.1285332", "author_list": ["Xue Zhang", "Mildred E. Warner"], "journal_name": "Community Development Volume 48, 2017 - Issue 2", "date": " 07 Feb 2017", "abstract": "This article explores trends in business retention and expansion (BRE) and business clusters over the last two decades (1994\u20132014). Using national surveys of local governments, this article finds that BRE has evolved from a focus on strengthening branch plants and their competitive links to parent firms to a broader emphasis on building local business cluster networks. BRE strategies have diffused across the nation, but business clusters are more common in metro core cities. Municipalities that have written economic development plans and use local funding are more likely to use BRE. This article finds cluster strategies are embedded in a broader set of community economic development strategies that strengthen quality of life and the foundation for community wellbeing. Unlike Michael Porter\u2019s emphasis on business clusters and competitiveness alone, this article finds economic developers recognize the need to focus not only on business clusters and competitiveness, but also on local services.", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.1080/15575330.2017.1285332", "keyword_list": ["Keywords:", "Business retention and expansion", "business clusters", "community development", "local services", "quality of life"], "citation_count": 0, "reference_list": ["Abatekassa, G., & Moser, C.H. (2002). Retention and expansion issues and concerns of rural businesses: Some findings from surveys in the Western Upper Peninsula of Michigan (Staff Paper No. 11638). East Lansing: Michigan State University, Department of Agricultural, Food, and Resource Economics.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Allanach, C., & Loveridge, S. (1998). An assessment of maximum-training business visitation programs. Economic Development Quarterly, 12, 125\u2013136. doi:10.1177/089124249801200202[Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Barkley, D.L., & Henry, M.S. (1997). Rural industrial development: To cluster or not to cluster? Review of Agricultural Economics, 19, 308\u2013325. doi:10.2307/1349744[Crossref]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bartik, T.J. (2003). Local economic development policies (Upjohn Institute Working Paper No. 03-91). Kalamazoo, MI: W. E. Upjohn Institute for Employment Research. doi:10.17848/wp03-91[Crossref]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bee, E. (2004). Small business vitality & economic development. Economic Development Journal, 3, 7\u201315.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bradshaw, T.K., & Blakely, E.J. (1999). What are \u201cthird-wave\u201d state economic development efforts? From incentives to industrial policy. Economic Development Quarterly, 13, 229\u2013244. doi:10.1177/089124249901300303[Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Bronstein, Z. (2009). Industry and the smart city. Dissent, 56, 27\u201334. doi:10.1353/dss.0.0062[Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Canada, E.P. (2003). The missing link: A vision for R&E. Retrieved from www.blanecanada.com/pdf/MissingLink.pdf\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Daniels, T. (2001). What does \u201csmart growth\u201d mean for community development? Community Development, 32, 20\u201334. doi:10.1080/15575330109489691[Taylor & Francis Online]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Delgado, M., Porter, M.E., & Stern, S. (2010). Clusters and entrepreneurship. Journal of Economic Geography, 10, 495\u2013518. doi:10.1093/jeg/lbq010[Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae]\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Florida, R.L. (2002). The rise of the creative class: And how it\u2019s transforming work, leisure, community and everyday life. New York, NY: Basic Books.\u00a0[Google Scholar]", "Fortunato, M.W., & Alter, T. (2015). Community e